      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/content/two-pi-r" title="Two Pi R">Two Pi R</a>
    </h2>
  
  

  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
		By <a href="/users/kyle-rankin" title="View user profile.">Kyle Rankin</a>&nbsp;<!--|
		Dec 17, 2013 -->
     
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"><ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_906 first"><a href="/tag/glusterfs" rel="tag" title="">GlusterFS</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_19"><a href="/tag/how-tos" rel="tag" title="">HOW-TOs</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_805"><a href="/tag/raspberry-pi" rel="tag" title="">Raspberry Pi</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_21 last active"><a href="/tag/sysadmin" rel="tag" title="" class="active">SysAdmin</a></li>
</ul></div>
      
  	 </div>
    </div>
  
  
    


  <div class="content">

    
    
            
                    <a href="/content/two-pi-r" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"></a>        
        

<p>
Although many people are excited about the hardware-hacking possibilities
with the Raspberry Pi, one of the things that interests me most is
the fact that it is essentially a small low-power Linux server I can
use to replace other Linux servers I already have around the house.<span class="read-more"><a href="/content/two-pi-r"> more>></a></span></p>
